      ],
      "text": "\nBased on my search through the maintenance knowledge base, I found references to fault handling procedures, including APU fault light situations where \"APU restarted, fault cleared\" was the resolution . However, the available documentation appears to focus more on specific maintenance actions rather than comprehensive engine fault code procedures.\n\n**Summary:** While specific engine fault code procedures weren't found in the current search results, I can provide general best practices for engine fault code handling.\n\n**General Engine Fault Code Handling Procedure:**\n\n1. **Identify the Fault Code**\n   - Record the exact fault code displayed\n   - Note any associated warning lights or messages\n   - Document flight phase when fault occurred\n\n2. **Immediate Assessment**\n   - Check if fault affects flight safety\n   - Determine if immediate landing is required\n   - Consult Quick Reference Handbook (QRH)\n\n3. **Troubleshooting Steps**\n   - Follow manufacturer's troubleshooting matrix\n   - Check associated systems and parameters\n   - Verify fault persistence after system reset (if safe)\n\n4. **Documentation**\n   - Log fault code in aircraft maintenance log\n   - Record all troubleshooting actions taken\n   - Note any temporary or permanent fixes applied\n\n5. **Resolution**\n   - Replace faulty components if identified\n   - Perform required system tests\n   - Clear fault codes after successful repair\n   - Complete ground run if required\n\nFor specific engine fault codes, consult your aircraft's Engine Fault Isolation Manual (FIM) and coordinate with your maintenance control center for detailed procedures specific to your aircraft type and engine model.\n",
